## ADOS-2 Module 3 Assessment Summary

**ID:** 21261  
**Type IDs:** 3  
**Category IDs:** 1  

### Description

A comprehensive observational summary template for the Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule, Second Edition (ADOS-2) Module 3. This module is designed for verbally fluent children and young adolescents. The template captures behavioural observations across communication, social interaction, play, and restricted/repetitive behaviours during the standardised assessment activities, supporting diagnostic formulation using neurodiversity-affirming language balanced with standardised clinical terminology. It is recommended that clinicians include their behavioural observations of the client as a note or added context, prior to generating the summary.

### Prompt

(The template below is designed for psychologists administering the Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule, Second Edition, also known as the ADOS-2, Module 3 assessment. This is a standardised, semi-structured observational assessment designed to evaluate social communication, reciprocal social interaction, imaginative play, and restricted/repetitive behaviours in verbally fluent children and young adolescents. Using the transcript, contextual notes, and observations from the session, you will generate a detailed summary of behavioural observations made during the standardised assessment activities. The summary should capture the child's presentation, behaviours across all domains, and clinical impressions in a way that balances neurodiversity-affirming language with standardised ADOS-2 terminology. Use the DSM-5-TR criteria and ADOS-2 framework when describing observations. Organise the summary under the following headings.)

<br>
#### ADOS-2 Module 3

Child Information:

* Child Name: [Print the client's first and last name.]
* Date of Birth: [Print the client's date of birth in Day Month, Year format.]
* Chronological Age: [Print the client's age on the day of the assessment in Years, Months format.]
* Date of Assessment: [Print the date of the assessment in Day Month, Year format.]

Attendance:

[CHILD NAME] attended the session with [CAREGIVER(S)].

Initial Presentation:

[Describe the child's presentation on arrival, e.g., calm / curious / anxious / distressed / engaged / withdrawn / tired. Describe engagement with the clinician on entry, e.g., approached readily / separated from caregiver easily / stayed close to caregiver / avoided eye contact / needed encouragement to enter the assessment room. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

BEHAVIOURAL OBSERVATIONS DURING ADOS-2 MODULE 3

**LANGUAGE AND COMMUNICATION**

**Overall Level of Non-Echoed Language (A1):**

[Describe the child's spontaneous, flexible use of language, e.g., used fluent and varied language across contexts / some repetitive or scripted elements alongside spontaneous speech / frequently used stereotyped or formulaic utterances with limited flexible language. Note the degree to which the child's language is self-generated versus echoed, scripted, or overly formal. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Speech Abnormalities Associated with Autism — Intonation, Volume, Rhythm, and Rate (A2):**

[Describe any atypical qualities in the child's speech, e.g., no notable speech abnormalities / mildly unusual prosody or intonation / markedly unusual intonation, volume, rhythm, or rate of speech that is atypical for the child's age and language level. Note any high-pitched voice, unusual stress patterns, or mechanical or monotone quality. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Immediate Echolalia (A3):**

[Describe any immediate repetition of words or phrases by the child, e.g., no immediate echolalia observed / occasional repetition of the clinician's words or phrases / frequent immediate echoing of clinician's speech. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Stereotyped/Idiosyncratic Use of Words or Phrases (A4):**

[Describe any unusual, repetitive, or context-inappropriate use of language by the child, e.g., no stereotyped or idiosyncratic language observed / some repetitive or formulaic phrases / frequent use of odd, idiosyncratic, or scripted language, including delayed echolalia, neologisms, pronoun errors, or arbitrary associations between words and meanings. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Offers Information (A5):**

[Describe the degree to which the child spontaneously offered information, elaborated on topics, or provided relevant details during conversation and activities, e.g., regularly offered information spontaneously and with relevance / occasionally volunteered information / rarely or never spontaneously offered information without prompting. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Asks for Information (A6):**

[Describe the child's use of questions directed to the clinician to gain information or maintain conversation, e.g., spontaneously asked relevant questions / asked occasional questions, primarily when directly prompted / rarely or did not ask questions of the clinician. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Reporting of Events (A7):**

[Describe the child's ability to describe past or non-routine events, e.g., provided clear, coherent, and detailed descriptions of events when prompted / gave brief or vague responses with limited elaboration / had difficulty reporting events in a meaningful or organised way / required significant prompting to produce any account of events. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Conversation (A8):**

[Describe the child's ability to engage in reciprocal conversational exchanges, e.g., engaged in fluid, reciprocal conversation with appropriate turn-taking and topic maintenance / responded to questions but did not elaborate or initiate topics / difficulty sustaining conversational flow or responding to conversational leads from the clinician. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Descriptive, Conventional, Instrumental, or Informational Gestures (A9):**

[Describe the range and quality of gestures used by the child, e.g., used varied and contextually appropriate gestures (e.g., pointing, nodding, demonstrating) integrated with speech / limited gesture repertoire / minimal or absent gesture use / gestures not well-integrated with verbal communication. (Note: Do not describe use of gestures unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")].

**RECIPROCAL SOCIAL INTERACTION**

**Unusual Eye Contact (B1):**

[Describe the child's patterns of eye contact, e.g., frequent and well-modulated eye contact that improved across the session / brief and inconsistent / fleeting glances only / reduced or avoidant eye contact during social bids / atypical quality of gaze. (Note: Do not describe unusual eye contact unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")].

**Facial Expressions Directed to Others (B2):**

[Describe the range and social directedness of the child's facial expressions, e.g., varied and appropriate facial expressions directed to the clinician / limited range of expressions / neutral or flat affect / expressions not clearly directed to or coordinated with others during interaction. (Note: Do not describe use of facial expressions unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")].

**Language Production and Linked Non-Verbal Communication (B3):**

[Describe the degree to which the child's verbal communication was integrated with non-verbal behaviours such as gaze, gesture, and facial expression, e.g., well-integrated coordination of language with non-verbal communicative behaviours / some integration but inconsistent / limited integration between verbal and non-verbal channels / language and non-verbal behaviours appeared largely disconnected. (Note: Do not describe the coordination of non-verbal behaviours unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")].

**Shared Enjoyment in Interaction (B4):**

[Describe the child's expression and sharing of positive affect during the session, e.g., clearly shared enjoyment with the clinician through gaze, smiles, and vocalisations / showed pleasure during activities but did not consistently direct this to others / limited or absent sharing of positive affect with the clinician. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Comments on Others' Emotions / Empathy (B5):**

[Describe the child's awareness and responsiveness to others' emotions, e.g., demonstrated clear understanding of and empathy for others' emotional states / communicated some understanding of emotions in others / limited or absent spontaneous comments on others' emotions or empathic responses. Note any specific examples from activities such as the Cartoons or Emotions tasks. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Insight into Typical Social Situations and Relationships (B6):**

[Describe the child's understanding of social relationships, conventions, and situations, e.g., demonstrated good insight into typical social relationships and contexts / showed some understanding of social situations / limited insight into typical social conventions or the nature of relationships. Note any relevant responses from activities such as Friends, Relationships, and Marriage; Loneliness; or Social Difficulties and Annoyance. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Quality of Social Overtures (B7):**

[Describe the appropriateness and integration of the child's social bids, e.g., integrated and appropriate social overtures / some social interest but overtures were poorly integrated or unusual in quality / minimal or absent social overtures. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Amount of Social Overtures / Maintenance of Attention (B8):**

[Describe the frequency and persistence of the child's social initiations and sustained engagement, e.g., frequent social initiations and maintained engagement with the clinician / occasional initiations / rarely or did not initiate social interaction or sustain attention to social interaction. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Quality of Social Response (B9):**

[Describe how the child responded to the clinician's social bids, e.g., responsive and appropriate to social overtures / inconsistently responsive / minimal or absent response to social bids from the clinician. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Amount of Reciprocal Social Communication (B10):**

[Describe the overall level of back-and-forth social engagement across the session, e.g., sustained reciprocal social exchanges / brief exchanges that required considerable clinician support / limited reciprocity / minimal or absent reciprocal communication. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Overall Quality of Rapport (B11):**

[Describe the nature of the relationship established between the child and the clinician across the session, e.g., warm and comfortable rapport that developed readily / some rapport established with support and time / rapport improved as the session progressed / limited rapport / minimal social connection. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**PLAY AND IMAGINATION**

**Imagination / Creativity (C1):**

[Describe evidence of imaginative and creative thinking observed across relevant activities, including Make-Believe Play, Joint Interactive Play, Telling a Story From a Book, Cartoons, and Creating a Story, e.g., demonstrated spontaneous and varied imaginative play with creative elaboration / showed some imaginative elements with support / limited imagination or creativity / play and storytelling remained concrete, repetitive, or reliant on clinician scaffolding. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**STEREOTYPED BEHAVIOURS AND RESTRICTED INTERESTS**

**Unusual Sensory Interest in Play Material / Person (D1):**

[Describe any atypical sensory exploration by the child, e.g., no unusual sensory interests observed / some sensory seeking behaviours (e.g., visual inspection, sniffing, mouthing of objects) / pronounced sensory interest in materials or the clinician's person that interfered with engagement. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Hand and Finger and Other Complex Mannerisms (D2):**

[Describe any repetitive motor movements or complex mannerisms, e.g., no unusual mannerisms observed / occasional hand flapping, finger posturing, or other body movements / frequent and prominent motor mannerisms. Note any facial grimacing or other atypical movements if observed. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Self-Injurious Behaviour (D3):**

[Describe any self-harm behaviours, e.g., no self-injurious behaviour observed / occasional instances (specify) / frequent self-injury requiring intervention. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Excessive Interest in or References to Unusual or Highly Specific Topics or Objects, or Repetitive Behaviours (D4):**

[Describe any intense, narrow, or unusual interests and repetitive behaviours, e.g., no excessive or unusual interests observed / showed notable focus on specific topics or objects, including frequency and nature of references / insistence on sameness or restricted play themes. Note any repeated references to specific characters, topics, or media across activities. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Compulsions or Rituals (D5):**

[Describe any ritualistic or compulsive behaviours, e.g., no compulsions or rituals observed / some rigid adherence to routines or sequences / notable compulsive behaviours or rituals that interfered with assessment activities. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**REGULATION, ATTENTION, AND BEHAVIOUR**

**Overactivity / Agitation (E1):**

[Describe the child's overall activity level and any signs of agitation, e.g., age-appropriate activity level throughout / some restlessness or fidgeting that was manageable / markedly overactive or agitated in a way that interfered with assessment activities. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Tantrums, Aggression, or Disruptive Behaviour (E2):**

[Note any tantrums, aggressive behaviour, or significant disruption during the session, including context and how managed. If none present, state: "No significant behavioural concerns noted during assessment." (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Anxiety (E3):**

[Describe any signs of anxiety observed during the session, e.g., no notable anxiety observed / mild anxiety at the start of the session that settled as rapport was established / notable anxiety across multiple activities that affected the child's engagement and performance. Include triggers and any observable behavioural or physical signs if relevant. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**CAREGIVER INTERACTION AND REPORT**

**Caregiver's Interaction Style:**

[Describe how the caregiver engaged with the child during the session, e.g., warm and responsive / highly directive / anxious or worried / observant but allowed child independence / required guidance to step back at times. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Caregiver Reports During Session:**

[Briefly note any relevant information shared by the caregiver about communication, social interaction, repetitive behaviours, sensory responses, daily functioning, or developmental concerns. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**CLINICAL IMPRESSIONS AND SUMMARY**

**Summary of Observed Strengths:**

[Describe positive observations and capacities, e.g., demonstrated fluent verbal language; engaged in reciprocal conversation in preferred topics; showed enjoyment during play activities; demonstrated some imaginative and creative thinking; showed emerging understanding of others' emotions; rapport improved across the session, etc. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Summary of Observed Differences and Areas of Support Need:**

[Describe patterns consistent with autism characteristics, e.g., differences in social reciprocity and social communication including reduced or atypical eye contact, limited spontaneous social initiation, reduced integration of non-verbal and verbal communication, limited gesture use, restricted range of imaginative play, repetitive references to specific topics or interests, and/or presence of repetitive behaviours or sensory sensitivities. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

