## ADOS-2 Module 4 Assessment Summary

**ID:** 21266  
**Type IDs:** 3  
**Category IDs:** 1  

### Description

A comprehensive observational summary template for the Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule, Second Edition (ADOS-2) Module 4. This module is designed for verbally fluent older adolescents and adults. The template captures behavioural observations across communication, social interaction, imagination/creativity, and restricted/repetitive behaviours during the standardised assessment activities, supporting diagnostic formulation using neurodiversity-affirming language balanced with standardised clinical terminology. It is recommended that clinicians include their behavioural observations of the client as a note or added context, prior to generating the summary.

### Prompt

(The template below is designed for psychologists administering the Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule, Second Edition, also known as the ADOS-2, Module 4 assessment. This is a standardised, semi-structured observational assessment designed to evaluate social communication, reciprocal social interaction, imagination/creativity, and restricted/repetitive behaviours in verbally fluent older adolescents and adults. Using the transcript, contextual notes, and observations from the session, you will generate a detailed summary of behavioural observations made during the standardised assessment activities. The summary should capture the individual's presentation, behaviours across all domains, and clinical impressions in a way that balances neurodiversity-affirming language with standardised ADOS-2 terminology. Use the DSM-5-TR criteria and ADOS-2 framework when describing observations. Note that there may be a parent, caregiver, or other support person in attendance during the assessment, and any relevant comments they make should be noted. Organise the summary under the following headings.)

<br>
#### ADOS-2 Module 4

Individual Information:

* Individual Name: [Print the client's first and last name.]
* Date of Birth: [Print the client's date of birth in Day Month, Year format.]
* Chronological Age: [Print the client's age on the day of the assessment in Years, Months format.]
* Date of Assessment: [Print the date of the assessment in Day Month, Year format.]


Attendance:

[INDIVIDUAL NAME] attended the session with [SUPPORT PERSON(S) / note if attended alone].

Initial Presentation:

[Describe the individual's presentation on arrival, e.g., calm / curious / anxious / engaged / withdrawn / guarded. Describe engagement with the clinician on entry, e.g., approached readily / required encouragement / made eye contact readily / avoided eye contact / appeared socially at ease / appeared socially tentative. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

BEHAVIOURAL OBSERVATIONS DURING ADOS-2 MODULE 4

**LANGUAGE AND COMMUNICATION**

**Overall Level of Non-Echoed Language (A1):**

[Describe the complexity and spontaneity of the individual's spoken language during the session, e.g., used sentences correctly including some complex speech with two or more clauses / some relatively complex speech but with recurrent grammatical errors not associated with dialect / non-echoed speech mostly comprised of utterances of at least three words but without complex language / non-echoed language made up mostly of simple phrases. Note that the rating should reflect the majority of the individual's utterances, not merely the best ones. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Speech Abnormalities Associated with Autism — Intonation, Volume, Rhythm, and Rate (A2):**

[Describe any atypical qualities in the individual's speech delivery, e.g., appropriately varying intonation, reasonable volume, and normal speech rate with regular rhythm / slight variation in pitch and tone, relatively flat or exaggerated intonation but not obviously peculiar, or slightly unusual volume or rate / speech that is markedly abnormal in intonation, volume, rhythm, or rate, such as slow and halting delivery, inappropriately rapid speech, jerky or irregular rhythm, odd intonation, or consistently abnormal volume. Note that articulation difficulties are not coded here. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Immediate Echolalia (A3):**

[Describe any immediate repetition of words or phrases by the individual, e.g., does not repeat others' speech / occasional echoing / echoing words and phrases regularly but with some spontaneous language / speech primarily consisting of immediate echolalia. Note that repetitions serving as a lead-in to a response or used as a memory aid in specific tasks are excluded from this rating. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Stereotyped/Idiosyncratic Use of Words or Phrases (A4):**

[Describe any unusual, repetitive, or context-inappropriate use of language, e.g., rarely or never uses stereotyped or idiosyncratic words or phrases / use of words or phrases tends to be more repetitive or formal than expected but not oddly so, or occasional stereotyped utterances alongside substantial spontaneous and flexible language / often uses stereotyped phrases or odd words alongside other language / frequently uses odd or stereotyped speech with rare non-stereotyped spontaneous speech. Note any instances of delayed echolalia, neologisms, pronoun errors across persons, or arbitrary associations between words and meanings. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Offering Information (A5):**

[Describe the degree to which the individual spontaneously offered personal information new to the clinician, e.g., spontaneously offered information about their thoughts, feelings, or experiences on several occasions / occasionally offered information spontaneously about their thoughts, feelings, or experiences / rarely or never offered information spontaneously, except about circumscribed interests or preoccupations, or offered information only about facts or general knowledge. Note that comments about facts alone are not coded here, and lists of multiple factors are counted as one instance unless part of compulsive listing behaviour. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Asking for Information (A6):**

[Describe the individual's spontaneous expression of interest in the clinician's thoughts, feelings, or experiences, e.g., asked the clinician about their thoughts, feelings, or experiences several times / occasionally, or at least once, asked the clinician about their thoughts, feelings, or experiences / responded appropriately to the clinician's comments about their own thoughts, feelings, or experiences but did not spontaneously inquire about them / rarely or never expressed interest in the clinician's thoughts, feelings, or experiences. Note that questions about test materials or unrelated topics are not coded here. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Reporting of Events (A7):**

[Describe the individual's ability to select and describe an event comprehensibly without requiring specific probes, e.g., reported a specific non-routine event (e.g., a holiday, a trip) that is not part of a preoccupation, providing a reasonable account without specific probes / provided a reasonable account of a routine event (e.g., a typical daily routine) without specific probes, including accounts from the Demonstration Task / provided an account of routine or non-routine events but dependent on specific probes, or described only an event that seemed unlikely to be real / inconsistent or insufficient responses even to specific probes. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Conversation (A8):**

[Describe the individual's ability to engage in reciprocal conversational exchanges, e.g., conversation flowed readily building on the clinician's dialogue, with the individual's speech providing both a response and additional content that allowed the clinician to continue (i.e., sequences of at least four elements) / speech included some spontaneous elaboration or conversational leads for the clinician's benefit, but less than expected for the individual's language level or limited in flexibility / little reciprocal conversation sustained by the individual, who may have followed their own train of thought rather than participating in an interchange / little spontaneous communicative speech with very limited responses to conversational initiations from the clinician. This rating should consider all opportunities for conversation, not merely the best. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Descriptive, Conventional, Instrumental, or Informational Gestures (A9):**
[Describe the range and quality of gestures used by the individual, e.g., spontaneous use of several descriptive gestures that enact or represent objects or events, which may be typical or idiosyncratic but must be communicative, along with conventional or instrumental gestures / some spontaneous use of descriptive gestures but exaggerated or limited in range or context (e.g., occurring only during the Demonstration Task), or frequent use of conventional or instrumental gestures with rare or no descriptive gestures / some spontaneous use of informational, conventional, or instrumental gestures but rare or no descriptive gestures / no or minimal spontaneous use of gestures of any type. Note that pointing is included here as an instrumental gesture and is not coded separately in Module 4. (Note: Do not describe gesture use unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Emphatic or Emotional Gestures (A10):**

[Describe the use of emphatic or emotional gestures by the individual, e.g., a variety of appropriate emphatic or emotional gestures well integrated with speech / some emphatic or emotional gestures but exaggerated or limited in frequency, appropriateness, integration, or style / odd, excessive, or awkwardly integrated emphatic or emotional gestures / no or minimal emphatic or emotional gestures. Note that the rating should be based on the timing of gestures as they occur during speech; integration of gesture with gaze is coded separately under Language Production and Linked Non-Verbal Communication or Quality of Social Overtures. (Note: Do not describe gesture use unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**RECIPROCAL SOCIAL INTERACTION**

**Unusual Eye Contact (B1):**

[Describe the individual's patterns of eye contact, e.g., appropriate, flexible, and socially modulated gaze used for a variety of communicative purposes and meshed with other forms of communication / poorly modulated eye contact that was limited in flexibility, appropriateness, or context when initiating, terminating, or regulating social interaction. Note whether eye contact improved as the session progressed, and note that eye contact between the individual and any support person present is not coded here. (Note: Do not describe eye contact unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Facial Expressions Directed to the Examiner (B2):**

[Describe the range and social directedness of the individual's facial expressions, e.g., directed a range of appropriate facial expressions to the clinician to communicate affective states (e.g., enjoyment, frustration) or cognitive states (e.g., puzzlement, scepticism) / some direction of facial expressions to the clinician, such as expressions indicating emotional extremes, or an individual with a limited range of expressions who directs almost all of them to the clinician / did not direct appropriate facial expressions to the clinician. Note that facial expressions directed to objects, other people in the room, or that are undirected are not rated here; appropriate or slightly exaggerated expressions should be coded even if there are also odd expressions. (Note: Do not describe facial expressions unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of it, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the client's verbal content alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Language Production and Linked Non-Verbal Communication (B3):**

[Describe the degree to which the individual's vocalisations were accompanied by coordinated non-verbal behaviours such as gaze, facial expression, and gesture, e.g., vocalisations usually accompanied by subtle and socially appropriate changes in body language, eye contact, and facial expressions / vocalisations accompanied by abnormal, limited, or less than usual frequency or range of gesture, gaze, and facial expression, or use of one modality almost exclusively / little or no non-verbal communication linked with vocalisations. Note that this item should be coded based on the vocalisations used, reflecting the most typical occurrences rather than merely the best ones. (Note: Do not describe the coordination of non-verbal behaviours unless the transcript contains explicit clinician observations of this, or contextual or clinical notes describe it directly. Do not infer from the verbal content of the client's speech alone. If no such evidence is present, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Shared Enjoyment in Interaction (B4):**

[Describe the individual's directed expression of pleasure during the session, e.g., showed definite pleasure appropriate to context during interactive participation or conversation with the clinician across more than one task or conversational topic / showed some pleasure appropriate to context during interactions with the clinician, or showed definite pleasure during one interaction / showed little or no expressed pleasure during interaction with the clinician, but showed pleasure in speech, actions, or non-interactive components / little or no expressed pleasure during the evaluation. Note that this item reflects the individual's ability to indicate pleasure to the clinician, not their general emotional state. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Communication of Own Affect (B5):**

[Describe the individual's ability to convey their own emotions using words, facial expressions, tone of voice, vocalisations, and body language including gestures, e.g., communicated a range of their own emotions effectively across descriptions and spontaneous comments / some description of experiencing several emotions but with limited communication effectiveness, or effective communication of at least one emotion / some communication about at least one emotion / minimal or no communication of their own affect. Note that descriptions elicited during the socioemotional questions (e.g., Emotions task) as well as spontaneous comments may be rated here, and that the rating should reflect the range of emotions and the effectiveness of communication rather than the specific emotions present. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Comments on Others' Emotions (B6):**

[Describe the individual's communication of their recognition, understanding, and response to the feelings of other people or characters, e.g., spontaneously communicated a clear understanding or labelling of, or appropriate response to, several different emotions in others or characters / communicated some understanding, labelling, or response to an emotion in at least one other person or character / little or no understanding of emotion in others. Note that shared enjoyment with the clinician is not coded here as it is rated separately. Note relevant examples from activities such as Emotions, Cartoons, or Creating a Story. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Insight into Typical Social Situations and Relationships (B7):**

[Describe the individual's understanding of the nature of social relationships and their own role within them, e.g., showed examples of insight into several typical social relationships including their role in at least one, with no more than one example of inaccurate understanding / showed insight into several typical social relationships but not into their own role, or showed insight into only one relationship including their role / showed some insight into one typical social relationship, though not necessarily about their own role / showed no or limited insight into typical social relationships. Note relevant responses from activities such as Friends, Relationships, and Marriage; Loneliness; Social Difficulties and Annoyance; and Plans and Hopes. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Responsibility (B8):**

[Describe the degree to which the individual presented as responsible for their own actions in typical daily living situations, responding actively and independently to normal social expectations, e.g., described themselves as responsible for their own actions across several contexts including dealing with minor problems in daily living / provided at least one clear indication of personal responsibility but inconsistent across contexts, with no more than one clear example of a lack of responsibility / showed limited indication of a sense of responsibility for their own actions, or showed more than one clear example of lack of responsibility appropriate for their chronological age taking into account developmental level. Note relevant responses from activities such as Current Work or School and Daily Living. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Quality of Social Overtures (B9):**

[Describe the quality of the individual's attempts to initiate social interaction with the clinician, e.g., effectively used non-verbal and verbal means to make clear, contextually appropriate social overtures / slightly unusual quality of some social overtures, or overtures restricted to personal demands or related to the individual's interests but with some attempt to involve the clinician / inappropriate overtures lacking integration into context or social quality, including bringing up preoccupations with little attempt to involve the clinician / no social overtures of any kind. Note that this item focuses on the quality of social overtures, not their frequency, and that the rating should reflect the majority of social overtures rather than merely the best ones. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Amount of Social Overtures and Attention Attempts (B10):**

[Describe the frequency of the individual's attempts to get, maintain, or direct the clinician's attention, including to objects, actions, or topics of interest to the individual, e.g., frequent attempts to get or maintain the clinician's attention or to direct the clinician's attention to objects, actions, or topics of interest / some such attempts but reduced in frequency or range of activities / occasional attempts to get, maintain, or direct the clinician's attention, including overtures solely related to preoccupations / showed relatively little concern about whether the clinician was paying attention unless needing help. Note that requests are not included in this rating except at the lowest level. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Quality of Social Response (B11):**

[Describe how the individual responded to the clinician's social bids, e.g., showed a range of appropriate responses varied according to immediate social situations and pressures / showed responsiveness to most social contexts but somewhat limited, socially awkward, inappropriate, inconsistent, or consistently negative / odd or stereotyped responses, or responses restricted in range or inappropriate to context / minimal or no response to the clinician's attempts to engage the individual. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Amount of Reciprocal Social Communication (B12):**

[Describe the overall level of back-and-forth social engagement across the session, e.g., extensive use of verbal or non-verbal behaviours for social interchange including chat, comments, remarks, or non-verbal behaviours with reciprocal intent / some reciprocal social communication but reduced in frequency, amount, or range of contexts / most communication was object-oriented, responsive to questions only, echolalic, or focused on preoccupations with little or no social give-and-take / little or no communication with the clinician. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Overall Quality of Rapport (B13):**

[Describe the nature of the relationship established between the individual and the clinician across the session, e.g., comfortable interaction appropriate to the context of the assessment / interaction sometimes comfortable but not sustained, feeling awkward or stilted at times, or the individual's behaviour seeming mechanical or slightly off / one-sided or unusual interaction resulting in a consistently mildly uncomfortable session that would have been difficult without the clinician continuously modifying the structure beyond standard activities / the individual showed minimal regard for the clinician, or the session was markedly uncomfortable for a significant proportion of the time. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**IMAGINATION AND CREATIVITY**

**Imagination and Creativity (C1):**

[Describe evidence of creative and inventive thinking observed across the session, either in the individual's use of objects or through verbal descriptions, e.g., demonstrated several spontaneous, inventive, and creative activities or comments in conversation / showed some creative or make-believe actions but limited in range or occurring only in response to one structured situation (e.g., Creating a Story) / little spontaneous creative or make-believe contribution, or only actions that were repetitive or stereotyped in quality / no creative or inventive actions. Note relevant observations from activities such as Telling a Story From a Book, Cartoons, and Creating a Story. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**STEREOTYPED BEHAVIOURS AND RESTRICTED INTERESTS**

**Unusual Sensory Interest in Play, Materials, or People (D1):**

[Describe any atypical sensory exploration by the individual, e.g., no unusual sensory interests or sensory-seeking behaviours / several possible sensory interests, or one clear occurrence of an unusual sensory interest or sensory-seeking behaviour / definite interest in sensory elements of objects or materials, or sensory examination of themselves or others, with two or more clear occurrences / unusual sensory-seeking behaviours occurring frequently across at least two different tasks or activities, potentially interfering with the assessment. Note that sensory aversions are not coded here, and that looking into a mirror is not considered an unusual sensory interest. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Hand and Finger and Other Complex Mannerisms (D2):**

[Describe any unusual or repetitive movements or posturing of the hands, fingers, arms, or body, e.g., no unusual mannerisms observed / possible or occasional unusual repetitive hand, finger, or complex mannerisms / definite finger flicking or twisting, or hand, finger, or complex mannerisms, stereotypies, or posturing that, while possibly brief or infrequent, were clear / mannerisms occurring frequently across at least two different tasks or activities. Note that finger tapping, nail-biting, hair twisting, and thumb sucking are not coded here, and body rocking is only coded if it involves more than the torso. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Self-Injurious Behaviour (D3):**

[Describe any behaviours involving any kind of aggressive act against the individual themselves, even if not harmful, e.g., no attempts to harm self / dubious or possible self-injury, or one rare but clear example (e.g., biting one's hand, pulling one's hair, slapping one's face, or banging one's head) / more than one clear example of self-injury such as head banging, face slapping, hair pulling, or self-biting. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Excessive Interest in or References to Unusual or Highly Specific Topics or Objects, or Repetitive Behaviours (D4):**

[Describe any intense, narrow, or unusual interests and repetitive behaviours, e.g., no excessive interest in or references to unusual, specific, or restricted topics, objects, or repetitive behaviours / occasional references to unusual or highly specific topics or patterns of interest occurring to a remarkable degree, or occasional repetitive behaviours / definite or stereotyped patterns of interest that may intrude on or interfere with social communication, or definite repetitive behaviours / definite preoccupation(s) or repetitive behaviours that interfered with the assessment. Note the frequency and nature of any such references and whether they were well integrated into conversation. Note that unusual use of language or lack of conversational flexibility is coded separately under A4, and that repetitive behaviours involving objects with a clear sequence are coded separately under D5. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Compulsions or Rituals (D5):**

[Describe any ritualistic or compulsive behaviours, e.g., no obvious activities or verbal routines that had to be completed in full or in a particular sequence not required by the task / unusually routinised in speech or activities (e.g., insistence on finishing a task or providing lists not relevant to the conversation) but without clearly compulsive quality / one or more activities or verbal routines that the individual felt compelled to perform or complete in a specific way, with apparent pressure or anxiety if disrupted. Note that the provision of lists should be rated here. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**OTHER ABNORMAL BEHAVIOURS**

**Overactivity and Agitation (E1):**

[Describe the individual's overall activity level and any signs of agitation, e.g., sat still appropriately throughout the assessment / sat but often fidgeted or moved about in the chair without principal disruption to the assessment / difficulty sitting, moving either in or out of the chair or handling objects in a mildly disruptive way / overactive behaviours that were challenging to interrupt and that disrupted the assessment. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Tantrums, Aggression, Negative or Disruptive Behaviour (E2):**

[Note any anger or disruption beyond mild frustration during the session, including context and how managed, e.g., not disruptive, destructive, negative, or aggressive during the assessment / one example of mild disruption, anger, aggression, or negative behaviour (including verbal threats, swearing, or deliberately loud voice) / more than one intentionally disruptive or negative incident / marked or repeated temper tantrums or significant aggression (e.g., throwing things, hitting, or biting). If none present, state: "No significant behavioural concerns noted during assessment." (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Anxiety (E3):**

[Describe any signs of anxiety observed during the session, e.g., no obvious anxiety / mild signs of anxiety or self-consciousness, especially at the beginning of the session or in response to specific activities / marked anxiety throughout the assessment, whether intermittent or continuous. Include triggers and any observable behavioural or physical signs if relevant. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**SUPPORT PERSON INTERACTION AND REPORT**

**Support Person's Interaction Style:**

[Describe how the support person engaged with the individual during the session, e.g., warm and supportive / highly directive / anxious or worried / observant and allowed the individual autonomy / required guidance to step back at times. If no support person was present, state: "The individual attended the session independently." (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Support Person Reports During Session:**

[Briefly note any relevant information shared by the support person about communication, social interaction, repetitive behaviours, sensory responses, daily functioning, or developmental or life history concerns. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank and do not print the sub-heading.)]

**CLINICAL IMPRESSIONS AND SUMMARY**

**Summary of Observed Strengths:**

[Describe positive observations and capacities of the individual, e.g., demonstrated fluent verbal language and broad vocabulary; engaged in reciprocal conversation on topics of interest; showed understanding of others' emotions; demonstrated creativity in storytelling activities; showed warmth and humour; communicated own affect effectively; rapport improved across the session, etc. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Summary of Observed Differences and Areas of Support Need:**

[Describe patterns consistent with autism characteristics, e.g., differences in social reciprocity and social communication including atypical or inconsistent eye contact, limited integration of verbal and non-verbal communication, reduced spontaneous social initiation, limited gesture use, restricted conversational reciprocity, stereotyped or idiosyncratic use of language, restricted range of interests or repetitive references to specific topics, limited communication of own affect, limited insight into social relationships, presence of compulsive or ritualistic behaviours, and/or unusual sensory-seeking behaviours. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Overall Clinical Impressions:**

[Provide an integrated observational summary using neurodiversity-affirming language balanced with clinical terminology. DO NOT PROVIDE DEFINITIVE DIAGNOSES. This section is to provide a summary of characteristics that assists the clinician to provide a diagnosis. Examples:]

[Option 1 — ASD characteristics observed: "Based on today's structured observational assessment using ADOS-2 Module 4, [INDIVIDUAL NAME] demonstrated a pattern of differences in social communication and reciprocal social interaction, along with restricted/repetitive behaviours and interests, that are consistent with an autistic neurotype / autism spectrum presentation. Specifically, [he/she/they] showed [list key observations across domains]. These observations should be integrated with developmental history, support person report, and other assessment data to inform the clinician's diagnostic formulation."]
[Option 2 — Mixed presentation: "While [INDIVIDUAL NAME] demonstrated some features associated with autism (e.g., [list specific observations]), other areas appeared more consistent with typical functioning for [his/her/their] age and developmental level (e.g., [list areas]). Further integration with comprehensive developmental history, support person interview, and additional assessment measures is required by the clinician to determine if the pattern of differences meets criteria for autism spectrum disorder."]
[Option 3 — Below threshold: "Although [INDIVIDUAL NAME] showed some individual features that can be associated with autism (e.g., [list]), the overall pattern of behaviours observed during today's assessment did not reach the threshold typically associated with autism spectrum disorder on the ADOS-2 Module 4. [His/Her/Their] social communication skills, reciprocal social interaction, and imaginative and creative contributions appeared broadly consistent with expectations for [his/her/their] age and language level, with [describe notable strengths]. These findings will be considered alongside other assessment data to help inform the clinician's diagnosis."]

**ADOS-2 Module 4 Algorithm Scores (if available):**

[If scores have been calculated, include here:]

Communication (A) Total: [X] (items A4, A8, A9, A10)
Social Interaction (B) Total: [X] (items B1, B2, B6, B8, B9, B11, B12)
Communication + Social Interaction Total: [X]
Stereotyped Behaviours and Restricted Interests Total: [X] (items C1, D1, D2, D4, D5)
ADOS-2 Classification: [autism / autism spectrum / non-spectrum]
Autism: Communication Total ≥ 3, AND Social Interaction Total ≥ 6, AND Communication + Social Interaction Total ≥ 10
Autism Spectrum: Communication Total ≥ 2, AND Social Interaction Total ≥ 4, AND Communication + Social Interaction Total ≥ 7, with at least one total below the autism cutoff
Non-Spectrum: Any total below autism spectrum cutoffs
[Note: Unlike Modules 1–3, the ADOS-2 Module 4 does not currently have a Calibrated Severity Score (Comparison Score). Algorithm scores are used directly to determine classification.]
[If scores not yet calculated, print: "Formal scoring and classification will be completed following the session using the ADOS-2 Module 4 algorithm and will be integrated into the comprehensive diagnostic report."]

**RISK, SAFETY, AND CONSENT**

**Risk and Safety:**

[If no concerns, print: "No immediate safety concerns were identified during today's assessment."]

[If concerns present: Briefly describe any risk behaviours, safety concerns, aggression, or self-injurious behaviours, and note actions taken or still to be taken. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**Individual's Engagement:**

[Describe the individual's apparent willingness to participate, response to transitions between activities, and overall tolerance of the assessment process, e.g., tolerated assessment well overall / showed some distress but was able to continue / required shortened session due to distress / engaged fully but with some hesitancy around specific topics or tasks. (If unable to make a judgment based on the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Unable to determine from available information.")]

**PLAN AND NEXT STEPS**

**Further Assessment:**

[Describe what additional assessment components are needed or planned, as stated by the clinician or support person. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Feedback Session:**

[Note plan for sharing results with the individual and/or family in a Feedback Session. Include time and date for that session, if known. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Additional Clinical Notes:**

[Note any factors that may have influenced performance, e.g., the individual's mental health presentation, fatigue, unfamiliar environment, support person anxiety, need for additional observation, co-occurring conditions that may affect ADOS-2 presentation (e.g., anxiety, ADHD, mood disorder, personality disorder), or any modifications to standard administration that were necessary. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

