## Adult Cognitive Assessment Report

**ID:** 15420  
**Type IDs:** 5  
**Category IDs:** 1  

### Description

Provides a draft adult cognitive assessment report. It is recommended that clinicians add files of any relevant assessment results (e.g., WAIS, Stanford-Binet, WASI, Kaufman, Woodcock-Johnson, Reynolds, ABAS, Vineland, SIB-R, ILS, W-ADL, etc.) before generating your report in order to obtain coverage of all results.

### Prompt

(Provide a detailed cognitive assessment report for a mental health clinician assessing an adult. Ensure that all information is attributed to its source, such as third party report, clinician observations, standardised assessments, etc. Provide your responses according to the instructions in the section headings below:)

Confidential

[Start on new line:]

Psychological Assessment Report

[Start on new line:]

Name: [Print the client's first and last name.]

[Start on new line:]

Date Of Birth: [Print the client's date of birth in Day Month, Year format. If unknown, print: "Unknown."]

[Start on new line:]

Age at Assessment: [Print the client’s age on the day of the assessment in Years, Months format. If unknown, print: "Unknown."]

[Start on new line:]

Client's Address: [If known, print the client's address. If unknown, print: "Unknown."]

[Start on new line:]

Assessor: [Print the first and last name of the clinician assessing the client, and their profession.]

[Start on new line:]

Measures Used:

* [Provide a list of the psychometric assessments used and quoted in this report. The list should be in order from oldest administered assessment to most recent administered assessment.]

[Start on new line:]

Assessment Date: [Print the date of the assessment in Day Month, Year format. The date printed here should reflect the date of the most recent assessment administered.]

[Start on new line:]

Report Date: [Print the date of this report in Day Month, Year format.]

[Start on new line:]

Documents Reviewed:

* [Provide a list of all the documents quoted in this report other than the assessments administered. This might include reports from other health professionals, case worker reports, etc. Include the date of these documents, if known, and the author and author’s title of these documents. The list should be in order from oldest document to most recent document. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]


<br>
***

<br>
**Referral Information**

[In a single paragraph, describe the reasons why a cognitive assessment has been requested for the client e.g., NDIS assessment, assessment of capacity for legal reasons, access to government resources, suitability for employment, etc. If known, indicate who has sought the cognitive assessment, who has referred the client, and any other information about the referral itself. When referring to someone other than the client for the first time, be sure to explain who that person is and what their relationship is to the client. Summarise the symptoms, behaviours, events, and situations that have led to referring the client for a cognitive assessment. Summarise when the onset of specific issues occurred, and how the specific issues have changed over time. Describe the impact on other aspects of the client's life, such as daily functioning, home / family life, social relationships, hobbies, and in any other area of the client’s life. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Background Information / Personal History**

[In a single paragraph, describe background information and any personal history that is relevant to the client’s current circumstances. Consider including information such as: legal issues; housing; ability to manage finances; ability to live independently; pregnancy issues or complications; other developmental issues (e.g., delays in reaching milestones, etc.); historical and current family circumstances (e.g., family relationship break-ups, etc.); historical academic difficulties; historical social issues; and historical adaptive functioning difficulties. Finish the paragraph with a sentence about the client’s strengths and/or special interests and hobbies. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Previous Assessments**

[Describe the results of any previous psychological, developmental, educational, speech-language, occupational therapy, physical therapy, or medical assessments and evaluations. Detail when any such assessments occurred, the name of the practitioner that administered the assessment, the profession of the practitioner who administered the assessment, and the key findings and recommendations. If no previous assessments are explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "No previous assessments have been completed.")]

**Medical and Mental Health History**

[In a single paragraph, describe the client’s medical and mental health history. Consider including such information as: previous diagnostic information (including when the diagnosis was made and by whom); current and previous medications; current and previous interventions (e.g., psychological therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, etc.); impact of diagnoses on the client’s daily functioning and the client’s ability to learn; and family medical and mental health history. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Current Concerns**

[In a single paragraph, summarise the current concerns for the client in relation to the cognitive assessment. Consider including information such as: current adaptive functioning difficulties; current neurological difficulties; current social difficulties; current employment issues, etc. Include both the client’s perspective, if applicable, and the perspective of any third party (e.g., case worker, parent / caregiver, guardian, etc.) if applicable. Describe the ways that the client or third party would like to see the client improve and specific goals they have for the client's development and functioning. This may include goals related to independent living, communication, social skills, behaviour, independence, employment, emotional regulation, or other areas. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**ASSESSMENT**

**Behavioural Observations**

[In a single paragraph, describe the client’s appearance and presentation; engagement and rapport; communication and comprehension; attention and concentration; motivation and effort; problem-solving style and working approach; emotional state and affect; and any other factors that may have influenced performance on any of the assessments. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Assessments Administered**

(In this section, you will provide information on each assessment administered. You will start with assessments measuring cognitive functioning and intelligence, then assessments measuring academic achievement, then assessments measuring adaptive functioning, then assessments measuring mental health, and then any other assessments used that fall into any other category. Note that different clinicians will use different types of measures, and not all reports will contain measures from all these domains.)

[For each assessment administered, create a separate sub-section with a sub-heading naming the assessment used e.g., Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale – Fourth Edition Australian and New Zealand Version (WISC-V); Wechsler Individual Achievement Test – Third Edition Australian and New Zealand Version (WIAT-III); Adaptive Behavior Assessment System – Third Edition (ABAS-3); Depression Anxiety Stress Scales – Long Form (DASS-42); etc.]

[For each assessment administered, below the respective sub-heading, provide an introductory paragraph describing the assessment. Consider including such information as: what the assessment is designed to measure; how the measure presents its results; summary of scales contained within the measure; and any other relevant information that helps orient the reader to why the measure was used.]

[For each assessment administered, below the introductory paragraph, provide as many paragraphs as needed to explain the client’s results on the assessment and what these results mean for the client’s presenting concerns. You must decide what results are most relevant to the client’s presenting concerns, and only include results that expand on the reader’s understanding of the client’s cognitive profile. Therefore, you do not necessarily have to include every numerical result on every scale of every measure used. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Diagnostic Impression**

[In a single paragraph, if known, describe the clinician’s diagnostic impressions and hypotheses, including the clinician’s differential diagnoses, and any other ideas expressed by the clinician around the possible reasons for the client’s presentation. If the clinician has not indicated any diagnostic impressions in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Clinician still to complete.")]

**Summary**

[Provide a concise summary in short paragraphs of the client’s reason for referral, the client’s assessment results, and a synthesis of all information. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

**Recommendations**

* [Provide a list of evidence-based recommendations in response to the results of this assessment. Consider including recommendations related to: the client’s employment and/or academic potential and performance; the client’s adaptive functioning; the client’s ability to live independently (either now or into the future); the client’s mental health, etc. Recommendations can be directed towards any of the following: family members; guardians; caregivers; case managers; employers; disability support services; referrals to other health specialists for further assessment; referrals to any other services; etc.]
* [List details of any future actions agreed on by the client or any other third party (e.g., family member, guardian, caregiver, case worker, etc.). This may include future appointment times.]

**Conclusion**

[In a single paragraph of less than four sentences, provide a summary of this cognitive assessment and any important ramifications for the client.]

[Print the following:]

While this report identifies areas where [client's first name] may benefit from additional support, it is important to recognise that [he/she] possesses strengths in areas not measured by these particular assessments. Building on these strengths may enhance [his/her]’s self-confidence, engagement, and overall well-being.

Additionally, performance on cognitive assessments can be influenced by various factors including motivation, attention, fatigue, anxiety, and circumstances on the day of testing. The results should therefore be interpreted as one component of a comprehensive understanding of [client's first name]'s abilities.

If you have any questions or would like to discuss any aspect of this report, please do not hesitate to contact me.

Yours sincerely,

[Clinician’s first and last name.]

