<br>
**Referral Information**

[In a single paragraph, describe the reasons why the parent, caregiver, or teacher has sought a cognitive assessment for the child client, emphasising the academic aspects of this referral. If known, indicate who has sought the cognitive assessment, who has referred the parent, caregiver, or teacher, and any other information about the referral itself. When referring to someone other than the child client for the first time, be sure to explain who that person is and what their relationship is to the child client. Summarise the symptoms, behaviours, events, and situations that have led to referring the child for a cognitive assessment, emphasising the impact on the child client's academic learning. Summarise when the onset of specific issues occurred, and how the specific issues have changed over time. Describe the impact on other aspects of the child client's life, such as daily functioning, home / family life, social relationships, hobbies, and in any other area of the child client’s life. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Background Information / Personal History**

[In a single paragraph, describe background information and any personal history that is relevant to the child client’s current circumstances. Consider including information such as: pregnancy issues or complications; other developmental issues (e.g., delays in reaching milestones, etc.); historical and current family circumstances (e.g., family relationship break-ups, etc.); historical academic difficulties; historical social issues; historical adaptive functioning difficulties; name and place of current school; current school grade. Finish the paragraph with a sentence about the child client’s strengths and/or special interests and hobbies. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Previous Assessments**

[Describe the results of any previous psychological, developmental, educational, speech-language, occupational therapy, physical therapy, or medical assessments and evaluations. Detail when any such assessments occurred, the name of the practitioner that administered the assessment, the profession of the practitioner who administered the assessment, and the key findings and recommendations. If no previous assessments are explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "No previous assessments have been completed.")]

**Medical and Mental Health History**

[In a single paragraph, describe the child client’s medical and mental health history. Consider including such information as: previous diagnostic information (including when the diagnosis was made and by whom); current and previous medications; current and previous interventions (e.g., psychological therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, etc.); impact of diagnoses on the child client’s functioning and academic performance; and family medical and mental health history. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Current Concerns**

[In a single paragraph, summarise the current concerns for the child client in relation to the cognitive assessment. Consider including information such as: current academic difficulties; current adaptive functioning difficulties; current neurological difficulties; and current social difficulties. Include both the child client’s perspective, if applicable, and the perspective of the parent, caregiver, or teacher. Describe the ways that the parent, caregiver, or teacher would like to see the child client improve and specific goals they have for the child client's development and functioning. This may include goals related to communication, social skills, behaviour, independence, academic performance, emotional regulation, or other areas. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**ASSESSMENT**

**Behavioural Observations**

[In a single paragraph, describe the client’s appearance and presentation; engagement and rapport; communication and comprehension; attention and concentration; motivation and effort; problem-solving style and working approach; emotional state and affect; and any other factors that may have influenced performance on any of the assessments. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Assessments Administered**

(In this section, you will provide information on each assessment administered. You will start with assessments measuring cognitive functioning and intelligence, then assessments measuring academic achievement, then assessments measuring adaptive functioning, then assessments measuring mental health, and then any other assessments used that fall into any other category. Note that different clinicians will use different types of measures, and not all reports will contain measures from all these domains.)

[For each assessment administered, create a separate sub-section with a sub-heading naming the assessment used e.g., Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children – Fifth Edition Australian and New Zealand Version (WISC-V); Wechsler Individual Achievement Test – Third Edition Australian and New Zealand Version (WIAT-III); Adaptive Behavior Assessment System – Third Edition (ABAS-3); Depression Anxiety Stress Scales – Youth Version (DASS-Y); etc.]

[For each assessment administered, below the respective sub-heading, provide an introductory paragraph describing the assessment. Consider including such information as: what the assessment is designed to measure; how the measure presents its results; summary of scales contained within the measure; and any other relevant information that helps orient the reader to why the measure was used.]

[For each assessment administered, below the introductory paragraph, provide as many paragraphs as needed to explain the child client’s results on the assessment and what these results mean for the child client’s presenting concerns. You must decide what results are most relevant to the child client’s presenting concerns, and only include results that expand on the reader’s understanding of the child client’s cognitive profile. Therefore, you do not necessarily have to include every numerical result on every scale of every measure used. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)]

**Diagnostic Impression**

[In a single paragraph, if known, describe the clinician’s diagnostic impressions and hypotheses, including the clinician’s differential diagnoses, and any other ideas expressed by the clinician around the possible reasons for the child client’s presentation. If the clinician has not indicated any diagnostic impressions in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, print: "Clinician still to complete.")]

**Summary**

[Provide a concise summary in short paragraphs of the child client’s reason for referral, the child client’s assessment results, and a synthesis of all information. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes, or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

**Recommendations**

* [Provide a list of evidence-based recommendations in response to the results of this assessment. Consider including recommendations related to: the child client’s schooling and academic performance; the child client’s adaptive functioning; the child client’s mental health, etc. Recommendations can be directed towards any of the following: parents and caregivers; teachers; referrals to other health specialists for further assessment; referrals to any other support services; etc.]
* [List details of any future actions agreed on by the parent, caregiver, or teacher e.g., future appointment times.]


**Conclusion**

[In a single paragraph of less than four sentences, provide a summary of this cognitive assessment and any important ramifications for the child client.]

[Print the following:]

While this report identifies areas where [child client's first name] may benefit from additional support, it is important to recognise that [he/she] possesses strengths in areas not measured by these particular assessments. Building on these strengths may enhance [his/her]’s self-confidence, engagement, and overall well-being.
Additionally, performance on cognitive assessments can be influenced by various factors including motivation, attention, fatigue, anxiety, and circumstances on the day of testing. The results should therefore be interpreted as one component of a comprehensive understanding of [child client's first name]'s abilities.

If you have any questions or would like to discuss any aspect of this report, please do not hesitate to contact me.

Yours sincerely,

[Clinician’s first and last name.]

