belief in any supernatural beings such as Santa Claus, which does not have to indicate the presence of psychotic thinking, but may match the child’s developmental stage and / or how the child is responding to any external life events; including any “flight of ideas” type thinking that may indicate that the child’s speech is unable to keep up with their thought processes); Thought Content (the content of the child’s thoughts, and note the presence of delusions, distortions, obsessions, or intrusive thoughts, if any; including any magical / fantasy thinking, the child referring to any imaginary friends, or the child’s belief in any supernatural beings such as Santa Claus, which does not have to indicate the presence of psychotic thinking, but may match the child’s developmental stage and / or how the child is responding to any external life events; including any tangential thinking that the child is having); Perception (hallucinations or other perceptual disturbances of the child, if any; including if the child indicates that these experiences are distressing, impairing, or inconsistent with typical play themes for a child of similar age; including the presence of any stated nightmares or night terrors, and distinguish these from any mistaken belief that they are considered to be perceptual disturbances); Cognition (the child’s orientation to time / place / person, attention, memory, concentration, and comprehension; including the results of any stated cognitive assessment that has previously been carried out on the child; including the child’s attention and concentration abilities); and Insight and Judgment (the child's understanding of their own difficulties and challenges, noting any age-appropriate lack of awareness or denial).]

