## Neuropsychological Assessment Report

**ID:** 4966  
**Type IDs:** 4,5  
**Category IDs:** 1  

### Description

A report providing a comprehensive overview of a neuropsychological evaluation.    When used with the “Create Document” feature, this template can integrate:  a) Pre-assessment interview (which can be recorded using the “Neuropsychology Pre-Assessment Interview” session template); b) Assessment sessions (using the “Neuropsychological Assessment Session” template); c) Feedback sessions (using the “Neuropsychology Feedback Session” template); d) Psychometrics completed in NovoPsych.    Note: The assessing clinician will need to input the neuropsychological test results, or can use the present template to “Dictate” and save the results. The output under the diagnosis subheading is intended as a decision-support tool only and not to be relied upon as a standalone basis for diagnosis. It should be reviewed carefully and integrated with the clinician’s expertise, judgment, and other sources of evidence.

### Prompt

(The template below is designed for neuropsychologists to create comprehensive assessment reports based on neuropsychological evaluations. This template will organise the background information, assessment findings, interpretation, and recommendations in a manner consistent with professional standards in neuropsychology. Analyse the transcripts, notes and contextual notes, and provide responses according to the instructions in the section headings below. Use professional, clinically appropriate language that is congruent with neurocognitive and neurodevelopmental disorders in the DSM-5-TR and ICD-11. Ensure a balanced presentation of both strengths and weaknesses, with clear connections between history, test findings, interpretations, and recommendations. Ensure the content is evidence-based. Always note where the information is coming from, e.g., “the [Client’s Name] said that”. Refer to the client using their name throughout the report. Do not print out any title at the top of the output.)

<br>
Dear [Recipient name (using appropriate title if applicable).] (If the recipient’s name is not stated, just write "Recipient Name".)

The following report is a comprehensive n​europsychological evaluation of [Client's Name].

### Information Sources

[List sources of information, including dates, clinical interviews, and psychometric assessments. When the clinician preparing the report refers to results for tests they have not conducted, identify the person who conducted the testing and state their qualification. Any person involved in the assessment should be named and their role and qualifications described in the report. (Use as many dot points as needed).]
[List the documents and other sources of information by third parties provided to the clinician to inform the contents of the report. This may include ambulance and hospital records, discharge summaries, nursing records if relevant, radiological reports or the reports of any other relevant investigations. Reports of subsequent investigation or intervention by any health professional, including neurologists, rehabilitation medicine specialists, psychiatrists, or other psychologists may also be included. Include any other neuropsychological assessment report and test results, an employer’s report (if relevant), or school reports if relevant. (only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).]

### Reason for Referral

[Using paragraphs, describe the specific reasons for the neuropsychological assessment referral. Detail the referring provider's questions and concerns. Document any specific diagnostic questions to be addressed (e.g., dementia evaluation, post-concussion assessment, capacity evaluation). Note any legal, educational, vocational, or treatment planning purposes for the evaluation. Include any specific questions the client or family members hoped to have answered through this assessment. Provide examples from the transcript, notes or contextual notes that illustrate the key reasons for seeking assessment.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

### Presenting Concerns

[Describe the primary cognitive, behavioural, emotional, or functional concerns that prompted the assessment as reported by the client. Document when these difficulties were first noticed and by whom. Detail the onset characteristics (sudden vs. gradual), progression pattern (stable, improving, worsening, fluctuating), and course over time. Note any precipitating events or circumstances associated with the onset of difficulties (e.g., head injury, medical event, emotional stressor). Describe the impact of these concerns on daily functioning, independence, work/school performance, and relationships. Provide specific examples from the transcript that illustrate the nature and severity of the current concerns.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

### Background History

**Medical History**
[Describe pertinent medical history, including neurological conditions, head injuries, seizures, stroke, surgeries, chronic illnesses, and other conditions that could impact brain function. Include dates of onset, treatments received, and current status. For each condition, note any cognitive or functional impacts reported by the client or documented in medical records. Detail any recent medical evaluations or imaging results relevant to the current concerns. Document current medications, including dosages and reported side effects.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

**Psychiatric History**
[Document any history of psychiatric conditions, including mood disorders, anxiety disorders, trauma-related disorders, psychotic disorders, or other mental health diagnoses. Include information about treatments received, hospitalisations, and current status. Discuss how these conditions may interact with cognitive symptoms or impact test performance. Note any current psychiatric symptoms.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

**Developmental and Educational History**
[Describe the client's early development, including any birth complications, developmental delays, learning difficulties, or early interventions. Please include any history of early developmental trauma, family or domestic violence or emotional or physical abuse. Detail educational history, including highest level completed, academic performance, special education services, learning disabilities, behavioural issues in school, and educational accommodations. For older adults, focus on educational attainment and general academic functioning rather than detailed early developmental milestones unless they appear directly relevant to current presentation.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

**Occupational History**
[Document the client's work history, with emphasis on recent employment. Include types of positions held, duration of employment, job responsibilities (particularly cognitive demands), performance, and any work accommodations. Note any changes in work status, responsibilities, or performance related to cognitive or other health concerns. For retired individuals, include former occupation, when they retired, and reasons for retirement. For students or those who have not worked outside the home, adapt this section accordingly.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

**Family History**
[Describe any family history of neurological conditions, neurodegenerative disorders, developmental disorders, learning disabilities, or psychiatric conditions, particularly among first-degree relatives. Note the specific relationship of affected family members to the client and their age of onset when known.] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Psychosocial History**
[Document current living situation, relationship status, and social support systems. Describe the quality and extent of social relationships and any changes in social functioning related to current concerns. Describe daily routines, leisure activities, hobbies, and community involvement, noting any changes due to current difficulties. Note any significant stressors, cultural factors, or other psychosocial factors that might impact cognitive functioning or assessment.] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Substance Use History**
[Detail current and past patterns of alcohol, tobacco, caffeine, and other substance use. Document frequency, quantity, duration of use, and any periods of heavy use or abstinence. Note any history of substance-related cognitive changes, withdrawal symptoms, or treatment for substance use disorders. Include information about recent use prior to testing sessions.] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Previous Assessments and Interventions**
[Describe any previous neuropsychological, psychological, cognitive, or medical evaluations relevant to the current concerns. Include dates, providers, specific tests administered, key findings, and diagnoses. Document any cognitive rehabilitation, therapy, or other interventions targeting cognitive functioning, including timing, duration, approach, and perceived effectiveness. Note baseline cognitive abilities if known from previous evaluations.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript, contextual notes or clinical note, otherwise leave blank.)

### Current Coping Strategies

[Detail strategies the client currently uses to compensate for or manage cognitive difficulties. These might include external aids (calendars, reminders, notes), environmental modifications, reliance on others, cognitive strategies, or lifestyle adaptations. Document which strategies have been most and least helpful. Note the client's level of insight into their difficulties and adaptation to changes in functioning.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the session notes, contextual notes, or transcripts, otherwise leave blank.)

### Client's Goals and Expectations

[Describe the client's understanding of the purpose of the neuropsychological assessment and their personal goals for the evaluation. Document specific questions or concerns they hope to have addressed. Note their expectations regarding diagnosis, prognosis, treatment recommendations, or other outcomes of the assessment. Describe their level of motivation and readiness for assessment and potential interventions. Write this as prose. Do not use bullet points.] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the session notes, contextual notes, or transcripts, otherwise leave blank.)

### Assessment Procedures

**Tests Administered**
[List only formal neuropsychological tests and psychometric assessments administered. Include full names of tests rather than abbreviations. Organise tests by cognitive domain. DO NOT include informal procedures other than specific standardised measures. Note any modifications to standard administration procedures and the reasons for these modifications. Document any formal tests that were attempted but not completed, including reasons for discontinuation.]

**Behavioural Observations and Mental Status Exam**
[Using paragraphs, provide a narrative summary of the client's presentation and behaviour during the assessment. Comment on appearance, level of consciousness, orientation, attitude toward testing, effort and motivation, response to frustration, fatigue, and other relevant behaviours. Document language abilities, speech characteristics, motor functioning, and other behavioural observations that could impact test interpretation. Note any inconsistencies in presentation across different testing sessions or between testing and informal observations. Discuss the validity and reliability of test results based on behaviour during assessment.] (only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

[Using paragraphs, provide a concise narrative summary of the client's mental status, and, where applicable, taking into account: Appearance (the client's general physical appearance, hygiene, grooming, and attire); behaviour (the client's interaction with their surrounds, activity level, psychomotor activity, eye contact, and rapport); speech (the rate, volume, tone, coherence, and articulation of the client's speech); mood and affect (the client's reported mood and emotional state, using their own words if possible, and the range and appropriateness of the client's emotional response during the appointment, noting any discrepancies with the client's stated mood; and any observations about emotional expression made by the clinician); thought process (the client's coherence, organisation, and flow of thoughts); thought content (the content of the client's thoughts, noting the presence of delusions, distortions, obsessions, or intrusive thoughts, if any); perception (hallucinations or other perceptual disturbances of the client, if any); cognition (the client's orientation to time / place / person, attention, memory, concentration, and comprehension); and insight and judgment (the client's understanding of their mental health presentation and their decision-making capacity, noting any lack of awareness or denial).] (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the session notes, contextual notes, or transcripts, otherwise leave blank.)

**Test Results**
(IMPORTANT: The sections below represent cognitive domains that may have been assessed through standardised testing. DO NOT include any domain that was not formally assessed using specific standardised measures. Only report on domains for which specific test scores (standard scores, percentiles, T-scores, scaled scores, etc.) are explicitly mentioned in the transcript or notes. DO NOT create new domains or infer results from behavioural observations or clinical interview. If a domain was not formally assessed with standardised measures, omit that section entirely. Be brief and technical.)

**Intellectual Functioning**
[Report results of intellectual assessments and premorbid estimation tests. Discuss overall intellectual functioning and any discrepancies between verbal and nonverbal abilities. Compare current intellectual functioning to estimated premorbid abilities based on demographic factors, reading abilities, or other estimation methods. Note any patterns suggestive of decline
from premorbid levels. (Relevant tests that the clinician might administer include the Test of Pre-morbid Functioning, Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scales or WAIS, or Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children or WISC).] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Attention and Processing Speed**
[Detail findings of standardised assessments related to attention and processing speed. (Relevant tests that the clinician might administer include CPT, Trail Making Test, WAIS Processing Speed index, D-KEFS, Conners Adult ADHD Rating Scales 2nd Edition or CAARS 2.] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Learning and Memory**
[Report results of standardised assessments of learning and memory. (Relevant tests that the clinician might administer include Wechsler Memory Scale or WMS, WAIS working memory index etc.).] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Problem Solving and Executive Functioning**
[Report results of standardised tests measuring problem-solving and executive functioning. (Relevant tests that the clinician might administer include Wisconsin Card Sorting Test or Trail Making Test). Discuss patterns of executive strengths and weaknesses and how these relate to everyday functioning and ability to compensate for other cognitive deficits.] (Only include if standardised test results are mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Language Functions**
[Report results of standardised tests assessing receptive language, expressive language, naming, fluency, comprehension, repetition, reading, and writing. Note any language-based deficits that could impact communication or other cognitive domains.] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Visuospatial Abilities**
[Detail results of standardised assessments examining visuospatial abilities and related skills. (Relevant tests that the clinician might administer include WAIS Visual Spatial Index, etc.).] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Motor and Sensory Functions**
[Describe findings from assessments of fine motor speed, coordination, strength, and sensory functioning if evaluated. Note any motor or sensory deficits that could impact performance in other cognitive domains or everyday functioning.] (only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Academic Achievement**
[If assessed, report findings related to reading, writing, mathematics, and other academic skills. Compare academic achievement to intellectual abilities and discuss any discrepancies suggesting learning disabilities or academic impact of cognitive deficits. (Relevant tests that the clinician might administer include the Wechsler Individual Assessment Test or WIAT).] (Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).

**Psychometric Assessments**
(Report psychometric assessment results under this separate subheading after cognitive test results have been reported)
[Provide any psychometric assessment results. For each test, include: the name of the assessment, a brief description of the psychometric assessment, the date of test administration, and relevant purpose to the current evaluation. Provide full quantitative results (e.g., scores, percentiles). Provide the full interpretation. Provide any implications of results in the clinical context related to the current evaluation. (Repeat this process for as many assessments as were administered.) If no psychometric assessments were administered, leave this section blank.]

### Formulation

[Provide an evidence-based formulation based on the integration of background history, behavioural observations, and test results. Present a narrative integration of quantitative results and qualitative observations rather than simply listing scores. Use evidence-based frameworks to connect test results to real-world functioning and presenting concerns. Note patterns of strengths and weaknesses within and across domains. Compare current functioning to estimated premorbid abilities and expected levels based on demographic factors, if there is evidence for this comparison. Do not make claims about typical cognitive profiles or causality unless explicitly supported by empirical evidence. Include evidence from the session notes, contextual notes, psychometric assessments, and transcripts to enhance the details of your formulation.]

### Diagnostic Impressions

[Describe the clinician's provisional diagnostic impressions and observations, based on DSM-5-TR and ICD-11 criteria. For neurocognitive disorders, specify the presumed etiology (e.g., Alzheimer's disease, vascular disease, traumatic brain injury) and severity level. List primary diagnoses first, followed by contributing or comorbid conditions. Provide the rationale given by the clinician for this diagnosis (or diagnoses), including details of relevant criteria that the client meets for such a diagnosis, and the test results which may provide evidence for or against a diagnosis being applied. Include the diagnostic code of any such diagnoses. Describe if the clinician has stated that these diagnoses are new or confirmation of diagnoses previously given. Document any differential diagnostic considerations that remain unresolved and require further investigation. Outline any relevant cultural, context, or trauma-informed considerations. (Do not over-interpret or make assumptions about possible explanations of the results or provide hypotheses about possible diagnoses. Adhere to what is known based on the results and the clinical observations. Only include if mentioned in a clinical note, transcript or contextual note, otherwise leave blank).]

### Summary

[Synthesise the assessment findings into a coherent neuropsychological conceptualisation that explains the client's presentation. Begin with a concise summary of key findings across domains. Discuss the pattern of cognitive strengths and weaknesses and whether these relate to the client's history, presenting concerns, and everyday functioning, only when direct evidence supports these relationships. Consider multiple contributing factors, including neurological, medical, psychiatric, educational, cultural, and psychosocial influences. Compare current findings to previous assessments if available to address questions of stability, improvement, or decline. Discuss how the findings address the original referral questions. Do not make specific claims about causality unless there is clear evidence to support such claims. Explain the implications of the findings for prognosis, treatment planning, and functional capabilities.]

### Recommendations

(Provide detailed, specific recommendations based on the assessment findings. Ensure recommendations are evidence-based, practical, actionable, and tailored to the client's unique circumstances, strengths, and challenges. Use numbered or bulleted format for clarity. Use the section headings below, where appropriate. Start the section with a statement “Based on the assessment findings, the following recommendations are made to support [Client's Name]'s cognitive health and psychological well-being:")

**Medical/Neurological Recommendations**
[Suggest any indicated medical or neurological follow-up or referrals to specialists. Recommend medication reviews if appropriate. Suggest sleep studies, pain management, or other medical interventions that could improve cognitive functioning or quality of life.]

**Cognitive Rehabilitation and Therapy**
[Recommend specific cognitive rehabilitation approaches, compensatory strategies, or therapeutic interventions targeted to the identified cognitive deficits. Suggest specific therapy modalities (e.g., cognitive-behavioral therapy, memory training, attention process training) that would address cognitive or emotional needs. Specify the frequency, duration, and goals of recommended therapies.]

**Educational/Vocational Recommendations**
[Provide specific recommendations for educational or workplace accommodations based on the identified cognitive strengths and weaknesses. For students, detail appropriate academic supports, accommodations, or modifications. For employed individuals, suggest job accommodations, modifications, or considerations for vocational planning. Address questions of educational or occupational capacity if raised in the referral.]

**Lifestyle and Environmental Modifications**
[Recommend lifestyle modifications that could improve cognitive functioning or prevent further decline, such as exercise, diet, sleep hygiene, stress management, or cognitive engagement. Suggest environmental modifications or compensatory strategies to support daily functioning, such as memory aids, organisational systems, or assistive technology.]

**Support and Resources**
[Suggest appropriate support services, caregiver resources, or community programs that could benefit the client based on their needs. Recommend support groups, educational resources, or other psychosocial interventions that could improve adjustment and quality of life.]

**Reassessment and Monitoring**
[Indicate whether and when reassessment would be beneficial to monitor cognitive change, evaluate treatment effectiveness, or address unresolved diagnostic questions. Specify which cognitive domains or functions should be monitored most closely in the interim.]

(Provide a paragraph in narrative form of 3-4 sentences, addressing the following:) [Indicate if test results and recommendations were discussed with the client upon completion of testing. Provide an observation of the client’s reaction to the results, e.g., “he was open to the feedback and seemed appreciative of the results.” Report any next steps agreed upon between the client and the neuropsychologist, such as additional follow up sessions. Report if the client’s questions were addressed as appropriate.]

### Conclusion

[Provide a brief closing paragraph that summarises key findings and recommendations, and offers continued availability for questions or follow-up. Express appreciation to the referrer and invite further communication as needed, e.g. “ If you require further clarification on anything contained in this report, please do not hesitate to contact me.”]

Sincerely,

[Clinician Name]
[Clinician Profession]
[Practice Name]

