* [Review of homework/sexual exercises: Briefly document progress with previously assigned exercises (e.g., sensate focus, communication tasks, mindfulness practices), focusing on key outcomes, barriers, and client responses. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript or contextual notes, otherwise leave blank.)]
* [Sexual experiences and communication: Document discussions of sexual experiences, physical sensations, intimate communication, and sexual functioning that occurred between sessions or during previous exercises. Note any significant revelations or concerns about sexual response, desire, pleasure, or intimacy. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript or contextual notes, otherwise leave blank.)]
* [Key topics discussed: Summarise the main sexual health issues, patterns, cycles or dynamics explored during the session and their relevance to treatment goals. (Only include if explicitly mentioned in the transcript or contextual notes, otherwise leave blank.)]

### Sexual Health Assessment and Dynamics

[Document sexual functioning, desire patterns, communication about sexuality, relationship dynamics affecting intimacy, and any physical or psychological factors discussed. Note relevant medical history, medications, or health conditions mentioned. Include relational dynamics around sexuality and intimacy.]

### Therapeutic Alliance and Engagement

[Briefly note engagement level and comfort discussing sexual topics. Document any resistance, shame, or collaborative moments observed during the session (use 1-2 sentences or bullet points)]

### Interventions

[Provide specific detail about all therapeutic interventions used and the therapeutic rationale. This may include sex therapy techniques such as sensate focus assignments, cognitive restructuring for sexual beliefs, mindfulness exercises, communication training, psychoeducation about sexual response, exposure exercises, as well as general therapeutic interventions such as CBT techniques, psychodynamic exploration, or systemic interventions. For each intervention, identify the specific technique, specify the therapeutic approach, detail what was targeted (e.g., performance anxiety, desire discrepancy, communication barriers), and summarise how clients responded, including any notable shifts in understanding or comfort level.] (Note: provide sufficient detail for another therapist to continue treatment. Use as many bullet points as needed for separate interventions)

### Progress

[Provide a concise summary of progress toward sexual health goals. Focus on clinically significant changes in sexual functioning, communication, intimacy, or relationship satisfaction. Note areas where progress is evident and areas that remain challenging.]

### Homework

[Describe exercises, communication tasks, or other assignments given to clients, including rationale and expected outcomes. Note any concerns or feedback from clients about the assignments. (Only include if mentioned in the transcript otherwise exclude section)]

### Risk Assessment

[Document any safety concerns, risk factors, or other clinical risks identified. Note any risk management strategies implemented or planned. (Only include if mentioned in the transcript otherwise exclude section)]

### Next Steps

[Outline the focus for the next session and any specific goals or exercises to continue. Provide the time, day and date of any future session agreed upon.]

### Summary

[Provide a brief recap of key points from the session in no more than three sentences, summarising the sexual concerns addressed, interventions used, client responses, and treatment direction.]

<br>
(Review the entire note to confirm that statements are consistently attributed to the correct individual throughout the note. Correct any inconsistencies to maintain clear and accurate attribution.)

