## Treatment Summary Report - Third Party Request

**ID:** 3180  
**Type IDs:** 5  
**Category IDs:** 1,2,3,4  

### Description

A concise report providing an overview of a client/patient’s treatment, intended for use with ongoing or past clients/patients, where a report has been requested by a third party (such as another health practitioner, legal representative, insurance provider or organisation such as a school or employer). It provides details of presentation, psychometric assessment, treatment received, and recommendations.

### Prompt

(Please write a concise, objective report providing an overview of a client/patient’s treatment. The report is to be provided to a third party who has requested information about a client/patient’s treatment. The report should not include any inferences, interpretations, or subjective assessments. Only provide details about treatment sessions, interventions used, progress made, and any documented statements or actions from the client. Ensure that all information presented is directly observable or stated by the client, with no speculative or interpretive language. Use the name of the client throughout the report. Use the below headings as a structure. Do not print out any title at the top of the output.)

<br>
Re: [Client’s Full Name]; DOB [Client’s Date of Birth.]

Dear [Recipient name (using appropriate title if applicable).] (If the recipient’s name is not stated, just write "Recipient Name".),

### Author Details:

I am [Record the name and qualifications of the clinician, and the purpose or reason for their involvement with the client.] I am writing in response to your request for information regarding [Client’s Full Name]’s treatment.

### Information Sources:

[List all sources of information used to compile this report, including: clinical records, session notes, assessment results, and dates of treatment. Specify the time period covered by this report.]

### Purpose of Treatment Report:

This report provides a summary of [Detail the reason for the request of the treatment report and who the report has been requested by. (Only include if mentioned in the client’s notes, transcripts, and contextual notes, otherwise leave blank.)]

This report is prepared from the perspective of a treating clinician and not as a forensic expert [Make it clear that the author is the treating clinician, not a forensic expert. Outline the subsequent scope and limitations of this report - for example, that the clinician can only provide information relevant to the client’s treatment and has not conducted any investigations outside the scope of treatment.]

### Presentation:

[Provide a concise statement regarding the reason the client sought or was referred for treatment, as documented in the initial assessment. Include the date treatment commenced, the presenting concerns, and the referral source if applicable. (Only include information that is explicitly mentioned in the client’s notes, transcripts, and contextual notes.)]

[Using as many paragraphs as needed, provide a concise summary of the client’s background, initial presenting issues, and initial goals for treatment. Using the client’s session notes, transcripts, and contextual notes, include information such as: the client’s initial presenting issues; other key client information such as circumstances, background, diagnoses and medical history, occupation, current living arrangements, and social support; trauma history; relevant people involved in the client’s life; and the client’s goals for treatment. If applicable, describe how any of this information significantly changed over the course of treatment. State the source of any information provided, for example by saying “the client reported that”. (Only include information that is explicitly mentioned in the client’s notes, transcripts, and contextual notes.)]

### Psychometric Assessments: 

The following psychometric assessments have been completed:
[Using bullet points, list the name of each psychometric assessment. For each assessment, you must include: 1) Assessment name, 2) One sentence description explaining what the tool measures 3) Results summary, and 4) Quantitative results (scores, percentiles, clinical ranges). If the same assessment has been administered on more than one occasion, only list the most recent and include any change in symptoms over time. (Only include information that is explicitly in the client’s psychometric assessments results, transcript(s), notes(s) or contextual notes, otherwise leave blank. If no psychometric assessments were administered, do not include the Psychometric Assessment section.)]

### Treatment:

[Using as many paragraphs as needed, provide a concise, objective summary of the treatment provided by the clinician. Using the client’s session notes, transcripts, and contextual notes, include information such as: date of first and last session; frequency of sessions; total number of sessions completed to date; treatment approaches used (e.g., CBT, ACT, schema therapy, psychodynamic psychotherapy); types of interventions used; types of homework or other activities completed as part of treatment; and the client’s engagement in treatment. Only include information that is explicitly mentioned in the client’s notes, transcripts, and contextual notes.]

[Provide an objective summary of the client's progress toward treatment goals, as documented in session notes, contextual notes and transcripts. Include quantitative measures or psychometric assessment results to support this, where available (e.g., reductions in symptom measures, functional improvements). Note any significant events or changes during the course of treatment that impacted progress (e.g., medication changes, life events, treatment interruptions). Document any periods of stability and/or symptom exacerbation, as recorded in session notes. (Only include information that is explicitly in the client’s psychometric assessments results, transcript(s), notes(s) or contextual notes, otherwise leave blank.)]

[Describe the client's most recent clinical presentation, as documented in the latest session notes. Include information about current symptoms, functional status, and any ongoing concerns. Document the client's current treatment status (e.g., active treatment, maintenance phase, discharged). If treatment has concluded, provide the date of termination and the reason (e.g., goals achieved, client decision, referral elsewhere). (Only include information that is explicitly in the client’s psychometric assessments results, transcript(s), notes(s) or contextual notes, otherwise leave blank.)]

[If treatment is ongoing, summarise the current treatment plan as documented in the most recent treatment plan update. Include current goals, planned interventions, and anticipated duration. If treatment has concluded, summarise any aftercare recommendations or referrals that were provided.] (Only include if applicable and explicitly documented in the transcripts, notes or contextual notes, otherwise leave blank.)]

### Recommendations:

[Only offer recommendations related to treatment, such as ongoing therapy or referrals to other professionals, such as engaging an independent psychologist for assessment and opinion if a request falls beyond the scope of the clinician.]

If you require additional information or have any questions about the contents of this report, please do not hesitate to contact me.

Sincerely,

[Clinician Name]
[Clinician Profession]
[Practice Name]

